programme.title: Wild Britain with Ray Mears
programme.desc: The survival expert explores the coastal landscape of north Norfolk, visiting shallow pools that are home to rare natterjack toads and a shingle spit that attracts hundreds of grey and common seals. He also finds out why the area has been dubbed Britain's bird-watching capital.(n)

programme.title: Wild Britain with Ray Mears
programme.desc: The survival expert visits the Breckland in East Anglia, which is home to an abundance of wildlife, including brown hares, stone-curlews and pool frogs, despite having the hottest summers and coldest winters in England. Ray also ventures below ground to explore an ancient flint mine known as Grimes Graves, where he uncovers the antler of a red deer that has been there since the Stone Age.(n)

programme.title: Operation Grand Canyon with Dan Snow
programme.desc: Part one of two. The broadcaster joins a team of historians and geologists to recreate a pioneering 280-mile journey through the natural wonder that was led by explorer John Wesley Powell in 1869. programme.desc: Huw Edwards explores the history of the country, and begins by delving into the world's largest prehistoric copper mine and visiting an Iron Age hill fort. He also reveals the scale of the Roman occupation and explains how Welsh saints shared the gospel with the rest of the Celtic world.(n)

programme.title: Cash in the Attic
programme.desc: Chris Hollins and Paul Hayes meet Nadine Hazel, who wants to raise money for two building projects by selling her collectibles at auction, including assorted items from her father's pub.(n)

programme.title: Antiques Roadshow
programme.desc: Fiona Bruce and the team travel to Cawdor Castle near Inverness, where members of the public bring along their treasured antiques and collectibles. Objects under scrutiny include original artwork given in payment for hairdressers' bills, the best bargain-buy dolls ever seen on the show and an early 18th-century travelling chest that may have once been owned by Queen Anne.(n)

programme.title: Time Team
programme.desc: Horse-owners Stephen and Stephanie Fry believe an 11th-century flour mill once stood on their land, and ask the experts to search for evidence. Mick Aston soon finds ample clues such as the remnants of millstreams used to power grindstones that suggest their theory is correct, but a problem arises when one of their finds does not fit in with the story.(n)

programme.title: Battle of Britain
programme.desc: Actor Ewan McGregor and his RAF pilot brother Colin look back on the pivotal Second World War battle, and meet brave souls who helped repel the Nazi Luftwaffe's relentless attacks.(n)

programme.title: Time Team
programme.sub-title: The House of the White Queen.
programme.desc: Tony Robinson and the team head to Groby Old Hall in Leicestershire, formerly the home of Edward IV's wife Elizabeth Woodville, and discover a surprising array of archaeological remains beneath its gardens, including a medieval wall and possible evidence of a Norman castle. They are joined by author Philippa Gregory, who delves into the complex history of the Greys, the house's former owners and one of the most powerful dynasties in medieval Britain.(n)

programme.title: Who Do You Think You Are
programme.desc: Following in the footsteps of Julie Walters, Sheridan Smith, Mary Berry and Billy Connolly, the last in the current series focuses on Twiggy. Four decades ago, Neasden-born Lesley Hornby, as she was known, found her life transformed when a reporter spotted her photo on the wall of a London hairdresser, and she was dubbed the `face of the 60s'. Suddenly the 16-year-old was catapulted into life as a supermodel, travelling the world, mixing with some of its biggest stars and eventually appearing in films such as The Boyfriend and The Blues Brothers. In the 100th episode of the genealogy show, Twiggy examines her family's past, where she discovers a history involving strong women and a hint of crime.(n)

programme.title: Cilla's Unswung Sixties
programme.desc: Cilla Black tells the real story of Britain's popular culture in a decade synonymous with music and fashion. Drawing on her own memories and experiences, the singer reveals what the British public was really wearing in the 1960s, the records they bought and what they liked to do in their spare time.(n)

programme.title: Coast
programme.desc: Neil Oliver visits a coastal amphitheatre near Land's End, Cornwall, where he performs an extract from The Tempest and learns how the venue came to be constructed. Nicholas Crane explores the history of a coach company that has transported northerners to the south coast since the 1930s, Miranda Krestovnikoff goes in search of a family of white-beaked dolphins, Adrian Gray demonstrates the art of balancing stones, and Alice Roberts finds out why the sea has its distinctive smell.(n)

programme.title: Forbidden History
programme.desc: Jamie Theakston travels to Portugal to meet leading experts on the Three Secrets of Fatima - a series of visions and prophecies allegedly given by the Virgin Mary to three young shepherds in 1917.(n)

programme.title: Code-Breakers: Bletchley Park's Lost Heroes
programme.desc: Keeley Hawes narrates the story of how a 24-year-old maths student and a GPO engineer unravelled the secrets of Adolf Hitler's personal code machine - reputedly even more secure than the Enigma device. The duo's work played an important role in ending the conflict in Europe, but because of its classified nature and continued application during the Cold War, the two men were never officially recognised.(n)

programme.title: The Lost Airmen of Buchenwald
programme.desc: Documentary revealing the story of the Allied airmen who were held at the Buchenwald concentration camp in the Second World War, featuring interviews with the surviving veterans.(n)

programme.title: The Story of Wales
programme.desc: Huw Edwards continues his exploration of the country's history by examining how, in 1485, Henry VII returned from exile in France to capture the English crown, becoming the first Welsh King of England. He discovers how the two countries became united under his leadership, leaving huge consequences for future generations, and explains the significance of being a landowner in the years that followed. The programme uses computer graphics and dramatic reconstructions to bring some of Wales' most historic moments to life.(n)

programme.title: Who's In Your History
programme.desc: Short film following people as they try to trace their ancestry.(n)

programme.title: Pagans and Pilgrims: Britain's Holiest Places
programme.desc: Welsh poet Ifor ap Glyn travels the breadth of the UK uncovering stories behind many famous holy sites. He explains the myths and legends of sacred places, including towering mountain hideaways and ancient shrines, and investigates what attracts people to them now their religious use is over. In this episode, he visits the ruins of St Andrews Cathedral in Fife, Wales' best-preserved Roman site, Coventry Cathedral and Whitby Abbey in North Yorkshire.(n)

programme.title: The Story of Wales: Power Struggles
programme.desc: Huw Edwards explores the ancient kings who shaped Wales as a nation, and how their battles with Vikings, Saxons and Normans made the local culture flourish. He then learns how the death of Wales's last native prince Dafydd ap Gruffydd was followed by a century of plague and famine, and what Owain Glyndwr's rebellion against the English Crown meant.(n)

programme.title: Victorian Farm
programme.desc: With the arrival of spring, Alex Langlands and Peter Ginn need to learn the skills necessary to deliver lambs and piglets. Along with Ruth Goodman, they have other livestock worries when a prized ewe is endangered, and a lame horse could jeopardise vital farm work. With their crops struggling, they turn to Victorian science for a solution, in the hope their hard work will not have been in vain.(n)

programme.title: Victorian Farm
programme.desc: Ruth Goodman is given a tough assignment at the dairy and Alex Langlands tries his hand at bee-keeping. As the summer days lengthen, Peter Ginn joins Alex for a game of cricket, and the trio find themselves in awe of a piece of rudimentary technology for shearing sheep. Soon, it is time for the hay harvest - weather permitting.(n)

Thriller based on Alistair MacLean's novel, starring Donald Sutherland, Vanessa Redgrave, Richard Widmark and Christopher Lee.(n)

programme.title: Rio Grande
programme.desc: A cavalry officer has to avoid showing preferential treatment when the son he has not seen for 15 years is posted to his fort as a cadet. His estranged wife also turns up wanting to take the boy away, but he is forced to put duty before his family when called on to rescue children kidnapped by Apaches on the Mexican border. John Ford's Western, with John Wayne, Maureen O'Hara, Ben Johnson and J Carrol Naish.(n)

programme.title: The Lady from Shanghai
programme.desc: An adventurer saves a woman's life, only to get involved in romance and intrigue on board her invalid millionaire husband's yacht. Murder mystery, written, directed by and starring Orson Welles, with Rita Hayworth, Everett Sloane and Glenn Anders.(n)

programme.title: Gideon of Scotland Yard
programme.desc: Police inspector George Gideon experiences an eventful day's work. He learns one of his detectives has accepted bribes, goes on the trail of a murderous maniac and tracks a woman suspected of robbery. He also helps foil a bank heist and gets off on the wrong foot with an eager young constable. John Ford's drama, starring Jack Hawkins, Dianne Foster, Anna Lee and Anna Massey.(n)

programme.title: Step Up 4: Miami Heat
programme.desc: An aspiring dancer comes to Miami to pursue her dreams, and falls in love with the leader of a street performance crew. When she learns the group's neighbourhood is to be demolished, driving the residents from their homes, she joins forces with them to organise a protest show. Dance drama sequel, starring Kathryn McCormick and Ryan Guzman. Edited for daytime broadcast.(n)

programme.title: Cuban Fury
programme.desc: A boy's dream of being a champion salsa dancer is shattered by bullies. Twenty years later, he returns to the dance floor as an overweight and under-confident adult, and tries to get his old footwork back in a bid to sweep his boss off her feet. Comedy, starring Nick Frost, Chris O'Dowd, Rashida Jones and Ian McShane.(n)

programme.title: The 36th Chamber of Shaolin
programme.desc: A gentle scholar becomes obsessed with revenge after his family and friends are murdered. Seeking out a Shaolin temple, he devotes his life to mastering the martial arts. Part of the Martial Arts Classics season.(n)

programme.title: Wild Things
programme.desc: A high-school counsellor is accused of rape by a student whose advances he spurned - and unfortunately for him, one of her peers backs up her story. Thriller, starring Neve Campbell, Denise Richards, Matt Dillon, Kevin Bacon, Theresa Russell, Robert Wagner and Bill Murray.(n)

programme.title: The Frogmen
programme.desc: Underwater demolition experts embark on a mission to find a safe landing site for the US military to launch an invasion on a South Pacific island occupied by Japanese army and navy forces. programme.title: The Three Musketeers
programme.desc: The king of France's elite personal guard is disbanded, but three of them refuse to lay down their swords. Aided by an impetuous young man keen to join their ranks, the trio set out to foil an evil cardinal's plot to seize the throne for himself by capturing the cleric's wily female spy. Swashbuckling comedy adventure, with Kiefer Sutherland, Charlie Sheen, Oliver Platt, Chris O'Donnell, Tim Curry and Rebecca De Mornay.(n)

programme.title: Carry On Up the Khyber
programme.desc: British forces in colonial India find themselves in deep trouble when a manic local ruler discovers the soldiers' fearsome reputation is thoroughly undeserved - prompting open rebellion. programme.title: Fast Girls
programme.desc: A fierce rivalry develops between a talented working class sprinter and the wealthy daughter of a former Olympic medal-winner as they compete on the track. programme.desc: A New York actor's difficult reputation has rendered him unemployable. programme.desc: Successful international smuggler Chris Farraday turns his back on a life of crime to raise a family. programme.channel: In the Heart of the Sea
programme.title: In the Heart of the Sea
programme.desc: In the winter of 1820, the New England whaling ship Essex was assaulted by something no one could believe a whale of mammoth size and will, and an almost human sense of vengeance. The real-life maritime disaster would inspire Herman Melvilles Moby Dick. But that told only half the story. Heart of the Sea reveals the encounters harrowing aftermath, as the ships surviving crew is pushed to their limits and forced to do the unthinkable to stay alive. Braving storms, starvation, panic and despair, the men will call into question their deepest beliefs, from the value of their lives to the morality of their trade, as their captain searches for direction on the open sea and his first mate still seeks to bring the great whale down.(n)
